00:25:19.750 --> 00:25:22.684
Weinberg to teach in the fall,
tells you that.

00:25:22.684 --> 00:25:26.148
And really where that
comes from is the fact that

00:25:26.148 --> 00:25:28.750
Salvador Luria had such an
interest

00:25:28.750 --> 00:25:29.968
in replication.

00:25:29.968 --> 00:25:32.811
So he trained Jim Watson,
started

00:25:32.811 --> 00:25:35.570
the Cancer Center here,
and he also carried out this

00:25:35.570 --> 00:25:37.126
phenomenon of
restriction.

00:25:37.126 --> 00:25:39.542
And he did this working with
bacteriophage.

00:25:39.542 --> 00:25:41.250
And I
know some of you wrote,

00:25:41.250 --> 00:25:43.373
you don't like to see old guys
on porches.

00:25:43.373 --> 00:25:44.616
So
I got freaked out,

00:25:44.616 --> 00:25:47.308
and I took this next picture
out for this morning.

00:25:47.308 --> 00:25:49.874
Oh, I've got to show it anyway
for two reasons.

00:25:49.874 --> 00:25:52.430
This is Salvador
sitting on a porch at Cold

00:25:52.430 --> 00:25:54.559
Spring Harbor with Max Delbruck
who

00:25:54.559 --> 00:25:56.426
started, really,
much of the work on

00:25:56.426 --> 00:25:59.837
bacteriophage that gave us the
underpinnings of microbiology.

00:25:59.837 --> 00:26:01.763
And I put it partly on A)
because

00:26:01.763 --> 00:26:05.291
it shows the informality of the
molecular biology culture which

00:26:05.291 --> 00:26:07.897
persists to this day,
and B) because Salvador had

00:26:07.897 --> 00:26:09.610
such an impish
sense of humor.

00:26:09.610 --> 00:26:12.349
You would have really enjoyed
had he been teaching

00:26:12.349 --> 00:26:13.022
this course.

00:26:13.022 --> 00:26:15.880
Anyway, Salvador was studying
just bacteriophage.

00:26:15.880 --> 00:26:17.355
Remember we talked about it?

00:26:17.355 --> 00:26:19.410
And they're basically a
syringe, they

00:26:19.410 --> 00:26:21.023
injected their DNA into the
cell.

00:26:21.023 --> 00:26:22.586
There's an electron micrograph.

00:26:22.586 --> 00:26:24.025
The
DNA is up top there.

00:26:24.025 --> 00:26:26.469
It goes in, and then the DNA
takes over the

00:26:26.469 --> 00:26:30.000
cell, reprograms it,
and makes baby phage.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:33.201
And I showed you how we make
plaques.

00:26:33.201 --> 00:26:36.780
So that was what Salvador
was studying.

00:26:36.780 --> 00:26:41.384
And it's a little like what we
are talking about with

00:26:41.384 --> 00:26:41.969
Mendel.

00:26:41.969 --> 00:26:46.490
He didn't have very many
techniques available to him at

00:26:46.490 --> 00:26:47.476
the
time.

00:26:47.476 --> 00:26:49.481
He couldn't sequence DNA.

00:26:49.481 --> 00:26:51.966
He couldn't do a lot of things.

00:26:51.966 --> 00:26:55.077
But he
could plate phage and count,

00:26:55.077 --> 00:26:56.810
and things like that.

00:26:56.810 --> 00:27:00.012
And what Salvador
was looking at,

00:27:00.012 --> 00:27:04.153
he had a bacteriophage,
and he had two

00:27:04.153 --> 00:27:06.457
strains of bacteria.

00:27:06.457 --> 00:27:09.107
I'll call them A and B.

00:27:09.107 --> 00:27:12.893
OK, here
comes the experiment that

00:27:12.893 --> 00:27:15.815
founded the biotech industry.

00:27:15.815 --> 00:27:17.125
You ready?

00:27:17.125 --> 00:27:19.066
You going to fund me?

00:27:19.066 --> 00:27:23.875
All right, so what I propose
doing is I'm going to

00:27:23.875 --> 00:27:29.690
grow the phage on strain A,
and now I'm going to plate on

00:27:29.690 --> 00:27:32.431
strain
A and strain B.

00:27:32.431 --> 00:27:36.887
I laid awake all last week
thinking

00:27:36.887 --> 00:27:38.576
of this experiment.

00:27:38.576 --> 00:27:40.176
So what did I get?

00:27:40.176 --> 00:27:44.976
I got a lot of plaques on
strain A, probably something

00:27:44.976 --> 00:27:48.442
like 10^9 or 10^10 per ml
because that's

00:27:48.442 --> 00:27:53.033
what this phage lysate usually
looks like once you've grown

00:27:53.033 --> 00:27:53.666
them up.

00:27:53.666 --> 00:27:56.697
And
if I plate them over on strain

00:27:56.697 --> 00:28:00.000
B, no phage, maybe an occasional
phage.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:05.148
So, obvioulsy the bacteriophage
can grow fine on strain A.

00:28:05.148 --> 00:28:08.708
It can't
grow on strain B most of the

00:28:08.708 --> 00:28:12.284
time, but some variant has
managed to

00:28:12.284 --> 00:28:15.310
figure out how to grow on
strain B.

00:28:15.310 --> 00:28:18.425
Given our foray into genetics,
I

00:28:18.425 --> 00:28:24.009
think many of you would think,
probably as I suspect Salvador

00:28:24.009 --> 00:28:25.621
did
at the time,

00:28:25.621 --> 00:28:27.376
the thing's mutated.

00:28:27.376 --> 00:28:28.517
It's learned.

00:28:28.517 --> 00:28:33.256
It's made some change
in its genomes that's allowed

00:28:33.256 --> 00:28:35.275
it to grow on strain B.

00:28:35.275 --> 00:28:40.139
So, I wonder if
it learned to grow on strain B,

00:28:40.139 --> 00:28:43.000
could it grow on strain A?

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:51.048
So, basically what he took was
the phage from that experiment,

00:28:51.048 --> 00:28:59.625
and then
he plated them on strain A and

00:28:59.625 --> 00:29:02.000
strain B.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:07.833
And, well, as you might guess,
since it was growing on strain

00:29:07.833 --> 00:29:12.238
B, lots of
plaques, and there were lots of

00:29:12.238 --> 00:29:14.119
plaques over here.

00:29:14.119 --> 00:29:19.056
OK, so it didn't
forget how to grow on strain A.

00:29:19.056 --> 00:29:23.000
So, better check over here,
too, need a

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:26.705
control experiment,
so take this guy,

00:29:26.705 --> 00:29:30.000
plate it out,
strain A, strain

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:32.716
B, some plaques over here.

00:29:32.716 --> 00:29:37.000
That's not a surprise going in
strain A.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:40.135
We are back to where we started
from.

00:29:40.135 --> 00:29:43.670
It doesn't sound like a
mutant, does it?

00:29:43.670 --> 00:29:47.799
And if it was a mutant,
everybody should have been

00:29:47.799 --> 00:29:48.504
the same.

00:29:48.504 --> 00:29:53.200
Instead, when you grew a phage
on strain A, it didn't have

00:29:53.200 --> 00:29:55.626
the ability to grow on strain
B.

00:29:55.626 --> 00:29:58.599
But if you gave it a chance to
grow

00:29:58.599 --> 00:30:04.000
on strain B,
most of them wouldn't make it.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:09.645
But if it ever did,
it had now acquired the ability

00:30:09.645 --> 00:30:11.900
to grow on
strain B.

00:30:11.900 --> 00:30:15.000
So it could still grow on both.

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:19.724
But if you take somebody who
had been growing,

00:30:19.724 --> 00:30:25.000
something had been growing on
strain A, it lost it.

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:30.541
And so, the idea there was then
that it wasn't a mutation.

00:30:30.541 --> 00:30:35.387
Something was
happening in the strain B that

00:30:35.387 --> 00:30:39.000
enabled it to grow on strain B.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:43.221
And if it ever got away from
that environment,

00:30:43.221 --> 00:30:44.253
it lost it.

00:30:44.253 --> 00:30:47.347
So, the
phenomenon was called

00:30:47.347 --> 00:30:48.525
restriction.

00:30:48.525 --> 00:30:50.587
It wasn't a mutation.

00:30:50.587 --> 00:30:53.090
It was
something else.

00:30:53.090 --> 00:30:57.855
And it turned out,
then, that restriction was

00:30:57.855 --> 00:31:00.013
due to an enzyme.

00:31:00.013 --> 00:31:04.453
An example of this kind of
thing,

00:31:04.453 --> 00:31:10.606
then, would be this EcoRI
activity that's able to cut at a

00:31:10.606 --> 00:31:13.190
very
specific sequence.

00:31:13.190 --> 00:31:18.269
Now, if you are going to have a
set of molecular

00:31:18.269 --> 00:31:23.913
scissors inside of you that
could cut at G A T C sequences,

00:31:23.913 --> 00:31:27.482
you'd have
a problem unless you did

00:31:27.482 --> 00:31:32.088
something else because every one
of your G A T

00:31:32.088 --> 00:31:39.000
C sequences would be cut by the
restriction enzymes.

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:45.814
So what the cells that have a
restriction enzyme have,

00:31:45.814 --> 00:31:49.250
is a
modification enzyme that

00:31:49.250 --> 00:31:54.428
recognizes the same sequence,
and then modifies

00:31:54.428 --> 00:32:02.142
it in some way that makes it
resistant to the restriction

00:32:02.142 --> 00:32:03.363
enzyme.

00:32:03.363 --> 00:32:09.298
And in the case of the EcoRI,
it

00:32:09.298 --> 00:32:12.451
puts on a methyl group on this
A.

00:32:12.451 --> 00:32:15.898
You might have thought that
that

00:32:15.898 --> 00:32:21.032
would interfere with base
pairing, but it doesn't because

00:32:21.032 --> 00:32:23.499
adenine looks
like this.

00:32:23.499 --> 00:32:28.098
These are the guys that base
pair with thymine,

00:32:28.098 --> 00:32:32.765
if you
look back, and you'll see that

00:32:32.765 --> 00:32:37.252
you could put a methyl
group in there.

00:32:37.252 --> 00:32:41.083
It wouldn't interfere with the
base

00:32:41.083 --> 00:32:43.165
pairing, but would allow this
to go.

00:32:43.165 --> 00:32:45.249
So, it was the discovery of
this

00:32:45.249 --> 00:32:48.753
phenomenon of restriction of
bacteriophage grew on one

00:32:48.753 --> 00:32:50.320
strain,
not on another.

00:32:50.320 --> 00:32:52.856
It could learn to grow on the
other strain.

00:32:52.856 --> 00:32:54.872
It could
lose that acquisition.

00:32:54.872 --> 00:32:56.222
It was that phenomenon.

00:32:56.222 --> 00:32:59.671
People, didn't have any
other reason other than it was

00:32:59.671 --> 00:33:01.915
an interesting problem in
biology

00:33:01.915 --> 00:33:03.204
to understand it.

00:33:03.204 --> 00:33:05.856
Once they understood the basis
of

00:33:05.856 --> 00:33:09.127
it, another whole world opened
up because you could see from

00:33:09.127 --> 00:33:11.398
basic
principles, now I could cut any

00:33:11.398 --> 00:33:12.164
piece of DNA.

00:33:12.164 --> 00:33:15.142
I could generate
these little overhanging sticky

00:33:15.142 --> 00:33:15.441
ends.

00:33:15.441 --> 00:33:16.999
I could take a plasmid.

00:33:16.999 --> 00:33:18.484
People knew about those.

00:33:18.484 --> 00:33:20.712
I could find one that only has
one

00:33:20.712 --> 00:33:21.699
restriction site.

00:33:21.699 --> 00:33:23.092
I could stick things in.

00:33:23.092 --> 00:33:26.385
Now I've attached an
origin of replication to each

00:33:26.385 --> 00:33:27.466
of those pieces.

00:33:27.466 --> 00:33:29.372
And I'm
in business.

00:33:29.372 --> 00:33:33.165
I can now, for the first time
ever,

00:33:33.165 --> 00:33:38.412
take a particular piece of DNA
and make as many copies as I

00:33:38.412 --> 00:33:38.864
want.

00:33:38.864 --> 00:33:41.232
And
that was an absolute

00:33:41.232 --> 00:33:45.829
transformation to the way people
were able to think

00:33:45.829 --> 00:33:47.134
about biology.

00:33:47.134 --> 00:33:52.163
So I'm going to just kind of
give you an idea of how

00:33:52.163 --> 00:33:54.015
people would start.

00:33:54.015 --> 00:33:58.498
So the way people began and
still begin most

00:33:58.498 --> 00:34:03.248
things is they'd call it,
the usual term is you call

00:34:03.248 --> 00:34:07.864
constructing a
recombinant DNA library.

00:34:07.864 --> 00:34:12.666
And there are a variety of
different

00:34:12.666 --> 00:34:15.525
ways of doing this.

00:34:15.525 --> 00:34:20.191
But this principle is the same.

00:34:20.191 --> 00:34:27.281
We'd take
the DNA from whatever organism

00:34:27.281 --> 00:34:33.689
you're interested in,
and studying.

00:34:33.689 --> 00:34:39.856
And we cut with some
restriction

00:34:39.856 --> 00:34:40.606
enzyme.

00:34:40.606 --> 00:34:46.928
And this restriction enzyme
will cut wherever there happened

00:34:46.928 --> 00:34:48.639
to
be sites.

00:34:48.639 --> 00:34:52.080
They might be close together.

00:34:52.080 --> 00:34:55.284
They might be far apart.

00:34:55.284 --> 00:34:59.025
But whatever,
still generate some

00:34:59.025 --> 00:35:03.000
characteristic set of fragments.

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:05.343
And we'll now have,
in this case,

00:35:05.343 --> 00:35:08.199
fragment number one,
fragment number

00:35:08.199 --> 00:35:11.618
two, fragment number three,
fragment number four,

00:35:11.618 --> 00:35:12.330
and so on.

00:35:12.330 --> 00:35:15.108
And if it's
my DNA, there's a lot of

00:35:15.108 --> 00:35:15.820
fragments.

00:35:15.820 --> 00:35:18.599
And of course,
they're all mixed up.

00:35:18.599 --> 00:35:21.089
I can't tell where any of them
are.

00:35:21.089 --> 00:35:23.798
They're just all mixed together
in

00:35:23.798 --> 00:35:24.992
the test tube.

00:35:24.992 --> 00:35:29.000
Then we'll take that vector
that we've opened.

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:34.439
And now, we'll mix all of these
fragments together with this

00:35:34.439 --> 00:35:35.362
vector.

00:35:35.362 --> 00:35:40.134
And then we join it just the
way we discussed.

00:35:40.134 --> 00:35:44.959
And now what
we'll get, it's a collection of

00:35:44.959 --> 00:35:48.826
plasmids that have different
inserts.

00:35:48.826 --> 00:35:54.452
So, one of the plasmids will
have that fragment number one.

00:35:54.452 --> 00:35:59.829
Another one of them will have
fragment number two,

00:35:59.829 --> 00:36:02.862
number
three, and so on.

00:36:02.862 --> 00:36:08.464
Then this whole thing is what's
known as a library.

00:36:08.464 --> 00:36:12.498
You can see if it's DNA from
me, there were 3

00:36:12.498 --> 00:36:14.702
billion base pairs to start.

00:36:14.702 --> 00:36:18.164
Given the human DNA,
G A T C sequences are

00:36:18.164 --> 00:36:19.314
pretty common.

00:36:19.314 --> 00:36:23.831
You can calculate the frequency
yourself for how many

00:36:23.831 --> 00:36:28.710
sites on average there would be
for a restriction enzyme within

00:36:28.710 --> 00:36:31.845
a piece
of DNA and figure out roughly

00:36:31.845 --> 00:36:35.164
how the fragments there would be
in the

00:36:35.164 --> 00:36:37.202
library of human DNA.

00:36:37.202 --> 00:36:39.626
So, we are partway there.

00:36:39.626 --> 00:36:41.857
We can
now make a library.

00:36:41.857 --> 00:36:44.214
We can make it from bacterial
DNA.

00:36:44.214 --> 00:36:46.571
We can make it
from human DNA.

00:36:46.571 --> 00:36:50.500
But the next thing that people
had to learn how to do

00:36:50.500 --> 00:36:55.500
was to figure out how to find a
particular fragment that had the

00:36:55.500 --> 00:36:57.536
gene that you are interested
in.

00:36:57.536 --> 00:37:00.045
And there's a whole variety of
things.

00:37:00.045 --> 00:37:03.114
I mean, ultimately today since
the human genome is sequenced,

00:37:03.114 --> 00:37:05.844
you go on a computer and type
and you find it because the

00:37:05.844 --> 00:37:07.028
sequence is
all known.

00:37:07.028 --> 00:37:09.938
But the only reason we can do
that is because of all the

00:37:09.938 --> 00:37:11.380
work that was done in between.

00:37:11.380 --> 00:37:13.351
So, I'll give you several ways
of doing

00:37:13.351 --> 00:37:13.601
this.

00:37:13.601 --> 00:37:16.160
But one of the ways I think you
can see very easily,

00:37:16.160 --> 00:37:18.586
and it's
actually going back to the term

00:37:18.586 --> 00:37:19.527
complementation.

00:37:19.527 --> 00:37:20.966
Remember
complementation?

00:37:20.966 --> 00:37:23.586
We had something that was
mutant, and then we'd put

00:37:23.586 --> 00:37:27.000
in a wild type gene,
and fixed it up again.

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:30.042
So, for example,
suppose I was studying

00:37:30.042 --> 00:37:32.435
histidine biosynthesis in
E.

00:37:32.435 --> 00:37:36.814
coli, and I wanted to find the
gene that encoded the enzyme

00:37:36.814 --> 00:37:39.469
that I
had just disabled in my

00:37:39.469 --> 00:37:41.369
histidine minus mutant.

00:37:41.369 --> 00:37:43.944
So, if I have a
his auxotroph,

00:37:43.944 --> 00:37:46.819
I'll call it a hisG gene,
for example,

00:37:46.819 --> 00:37:50.737
that's one of
the genes involved in making

00:37:50.737 --> 00:37:51.664
histidine.

00:37:51.664 --> 00:37:54.895
So, since it's a
histidine auxotroph,

00:37:54.895 --> 00:37:58.052
if I have it on just minimal
glucose plates,

00:37:58.052 --> 00:38:00.660
and I
streak it out,

00:38:00.660 --> 00:38:04.000
it's not going to grow.

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:08.623
But if I grow it on minimal
glucose plus histidine,

00:38:08.623 --> 00:38:12.284
then it will be able
to grow, right?

00:38:12.284 --> 00:38:16.272
So, I've got a variant of this
organism.

00:38:16.272 --> 00:38:20.615
It's got
a single mutation in it that's

00:38:20.615 --> 00:38:22.588
affecting one gene.

00:38:22.588 --> 00:38:27.331
And because I
don't have that gene,

00:38:27.331 --> 00:38:31.000
I can't grow on minimal.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:34.881
If I made a library of E.
coli DNA, which is going to

00:38:34.881 --> 00:38:37.460
have a lot of
fragments as well,

00:38:37.460 --> 00:38:41.152
and I took that library and I
put it into this

00:38:41.152 --> 00:38:44.666
mutant, I'm going to get a big
mess of things,

00:38:44.666 --> 00:38:48.542
all the different
plasmids with all the different

00:38:48.542 --> 00:38:51.304
fragments that go into that
mutant.

00:38:51.304 --> 00:38:54.308
How am I going to find the one
that I want?

00:38:54.308 --> 00:38:55.523
Anybody see that?

00:38:55.523 --> 00:38:57.087
It's not
that hard.

00:38:57.087 --> 00:38:58.145
I'm the mutant.

00:38:58.145 --> 00:39:01.460
I can't grow on minimal because
I can't make

00:39:01.460 --> 00:39:02.874
this enzyme.

00:39:02.874 --> 00:39:07.000
Therefore, I can't make
histidine.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:08.323
What do I need?

00:39:08.323 --> 00:39:12.205
How could you fix me up if you
were a doctor?

00:39:12.205 --> 00:39:15.718
What's
the gene we want out of here?

00:39:15.718 --> 00:39:19.000
The one that makes that
particular

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:21.400
enzyme that makes histidine.

00:39:21.400 --> 00:39:25.000
Yeah, take the whole library,
stick it in

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:26.090
this mutant.

00:39:26.090 --> 00:39:30.090
If the gene coming in encodes
DNA polymerase,

00:39:30.090 --> 00:39:33.429
I'm not
going to help this guy.

00:39:33.429 --> 00:39:37.443
It still won't grow in minimal,
take

00:39:37.443 --> 00:39:43.233
a gene involved in making part
of the cell wall won't help.

00:39:43.233 --> 00:39:47.382
But if I
put in the, I get a fragment of

00:39:47.382 --> 00:39:51.219
DNA that includes the hisG plus
gene,

00:39:51.219 --> 00:39:55.334
and I put it in here,
it's going to grow up.

00:39:55.334 --> 00:40:01.494
If it has the plasmid that
has, or let's say the vector

00:40:01.494 --> 00:40:05.000
